payload.comments:
Some general notes to finish:

I found the ‘most at home’ question interesting and as I think it really depends on my mood and the wider context. Most of these I would find interesting as a live performance as long as there was variation throughout the live set. If it was that one clip or v similar for the whole performance that would be less compelling but I don’t think any liver performance is like that in reality.

I ended up rating based on what I thought fitted that environment / setting best.

Also, I didn’t choose this option often based on the above but I believe that almost all of these could be used for workshop / education as the actual output is less important there in my opinion. I chose this mostly where it didn’t fit into the other three categories.

Final thing - I listened to most of these through a nice set of over ear headphones. For comparison’s sake I did side by side tests of a couple with laptop speakers and much preferred the headphone version - the bass notes come through much clearer and make the whole thing more balanced

I didn't feel synchronization or coherence which made it overstimulated. Felt like audio was randomly composed by a human, and visuals were randomly composed by a computer, without knowledge of each other. It lost interest quickly, and the clip felt long.

Much more synchronized between audio and visual than the previous clip. Felt like computerized composition (Bee-pe-re-boop-boop!) More enjoyable to watch because of synchronization, however pacing/speed of delivery was VERY fast and became overstimulating once audio paired with visual. I think the visual was especially fatiguing bouncing around, though it helped to have less color saturation on the hexagon revealing more pattern. With the audio, the overstimulation came from discontinuity between high sounds and low sounds with seemingly no order or grounding feature. The only grounding feature to me was the fact that audio and visuals were in sync.

This clip finally made things click - I felt like I was learning. I picked up that the top orientation was very the low bass sounds and the bottom orientation was for the highest sounds, and there was a gradation of low to high sounds visually oriented top to bottom. While i haven't learned the colors for pitches yet, I understand that there's an underlying order, and orientation made a big difference. It added for me another cohering factor that made it very enjoyable to watch. It made me want to play with the unit.

This clip seemed more harmonic - driven by audio composition first. I think I experienced sequences, and pacing of delivery was moderate. I thought it may have been more human composed, but perhaps there were more parameters on harmonicity for a computer-driven algorithmic composition. It felt hypnotic and was the first clip I wanted to replay, and played/watched/listened twice. I thought it would be suitable for background ambiance or an installation. I am finding the synth sound used a little harsh throughout all clips - but this composition was more enjoyable and felt like wind chimes.

I couldn't help but think there was a human on a keyboard behind the scenes just randomly inputting sound, and seeking some visual pattern. It felt pretty random and then got faster and faster once a pattern was found. The experience was incoherent to me and felt more like a live exploration of cause-and-effect that I was experiencing recorded.

I finally learned that blue is F#/Gb, pink is A#/Bb, and violet is G#/Ab. The limitations on colors and pitch in this mode really helped, and even if the composition felt random, having less pitch/color parameters made it much more enjoyable for me to watch and listen. I enjoyed it at this pace, and would probably enjoy it even more with delivery at half speed or slower. I couldn't tell if it was human or computer generated, but it's certainly something that a human COULD compose.

This clip was very interesting to me. I suddenly wondered why fifths were close together in color, and also wondered why the same pitches were recurring in wildly different visual areas than I expected them to since I last had heard that pitch. I felt like the colors were "surprising" me as to their location, and therefore randomized in location, while the audio was much more sequential and coherent. it felt jazzy and chill, and I would definitely not mine listening to that as background ambience music with lights going on in this clip that I wouldn't have to pay much attention to. However, since I was focused in this study, the randomness of color location captured most of my attention and detracted from my enjoyment of the audio composition.
The full sudden fillings of the unit with color felt overwhelming and unhelpful. I felt I was going a little cross eyed trying to experience pattern through an absence of color.

Interestingly this one started to feel more impressionistic (like Debussy). There was more gradual color shifting and what sounded like extended harmonies and rhythms that were more intentional than previous clips. I enjoyed it and the moments that brought down my liking rating was when it quickly got too "busy" visually and perhaps added what felt like destructive interference. (I admit for the differentiation of "constructive" and "destructive" interference has been a bit ambiguous for me to define so far.)

The sense of rhythmic pulse and rhythms in the composition at a digestible pace made this composition very enjoyable for me, even if pitches were leaping. The visuals reinforced the experience and made it enjoyable to watch while listening. I enjoyed the coherence and started bopping my head do it, feeling rhythm in my body in this clip. I liked it a lot - felt it must be human led. I'd dig that in a live-performance setting.
